description: Enforce skeleton loading states for every async component
globs: **/*.tsx
alwaysApply: false
---

# Loading States

Every component that fetches async data **must** implement a skeleton loading state.

## Required pattern

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
const [data, setData] = useState<T | null>(null);
const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(true);
const [error, setError] = useState<Error | null>(null);

if (isLoading) return <SessionCardSkeleton />;
if (error) return <ErrorState message={error.message} />;
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — renders nothing while loading
const [data, setData] = useState<T | null>(null);
useEffect(() => { fetch().then(setData); }, []);
if (!data) return null;
```

## Skeleton components

Use the Shadcn `<Skeleton>` primitive to build skeleton variants. Name them `<ComponentNameSkeleton>` and colocate with the component.

```tsx
import { Skeleton } from "@/components/ui/skeleton";

export function SessionCardSkeleton() {
  return (
    <div className="p-4 space-y-2">
      <Skeleton className="h-4 w-3/4" />
      <Skeleton className="h-4 w-1/2" />
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Supabase queries

Always destructure `{ data, error }` and track loading state explicitly:

```tsx
const { data, error, isLoading } = useQuery(...);
// or with raw supabase client:
setIsLoading(true);
const { data, error } = await supabase.from("sessions").select("*");
setIsLoading(false);
```

## Rule

- Every `async` data fetch → paired loading + error state
- Every loading state → Shadcn `<Skeleton>` (not a spinner, not `null`)
- No component renders `null` as its only loading representation
